                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">Smith</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_MVM1"
                            >Molotov</persName> Meeting, Geneva, June 18, Evening: Editorial
                        Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>This meeting, which was held at <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">Smith</persName>’s
                    request, was reported to the Department of State in telegram <gloss
                        target="#t_Dulte1">Dulte</gloss> 202, June 19, from Geneva. Most of the
                    discussion dealt with Indochina; for the complete text of <pb facs="0419"
                        n="393" xml:id="pg_393"/> the telegram, see <ref target="#pg_1189">page
                        1189</ref>. Concerning Korea, <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">Smith</persName>
                    made the following brief comment: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“With regard to Korean phase, I had only to say that in reserving our
                            position re final Chinese proposal had not implied to exclude Communist
                            China from future discussions on Korean question. As matter of fact,
                            China was belligerent there against <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>
                            and for practical reasons would have to be party to settlement.” (396.1
                            GE/6–1954)</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
